    <h1>Scaffolded Guided Notes</h1>
    <p class="subtitle">A catalog-wide resource system built to give all learners a common starting point.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="content">

    <p>After years working with faculty and students and looking at course data, I kept noticing the same tension: students arrive with very different levels of preparation. Good content alone doesn't close that gap. Students who already know how to learn have a structural advantage, and in a fully digital environment, that gap can actually get wider.</p>

    <p>The debate I kept having with colleagues was about whether students should develop their own note-taking strategies. I agreed that's a worthy goal. But withholding scaffolding in the name of skill-building isn't the same as helping students build skills. I wanted to give every student a common baseline to work from.</p>

    <div class="insight-row">
      <div class="insight-card"><h3>Learner Gap</h3><p>Students entered with uneven study strategies. Digital-only content offered no physical touchpoint or organizational scaffold.</p></div>
      <div class="insight-card"><h3>Equity Gap</h3><p>Students from under-resourced backgrounds were most disadvantaged by the absence of structured support materials.</p></div>
      <div class="insight-card"><h3>Alignment Gap</h3><p>Instructor-written exams sometimes diverged from courseware emphasis, leaving students without a clear map of priorities.</p></div>
      <div class="insight-card"><h3>Physical Gap</h3><p>Student feedback revealed a persistent desire for something tangible — material they could print, hold, and write in.</p></div>
    </div>

    <p>I built guided notes for Lumen's courses: printable Google Docs that follow each module's structure, organized around the same section headers students see in the course. The format combines fill-in-the-blank vocabulary, hierarchical outlines, and occasional reflection prompts. Students get a map of how the content fits together without having the thinking done for them.</p>

    <p>The choice to use Google Docs was deliberate. They're universally accessible, easily copied and modified, and printable with no special login required. Students said they wanted something physical they could hold and write in, and Google Docs delivered that without adding any barriers.</p>

    <p>The first set was built entirely by hand. I worked through every module myself, reading the content and making decisions about what to include and what to leave out. It was time-consuming, but that direct engagement shaped the quality of what I built. When ChatGPT became available, I created custom GPTs trained on the course content and my formatting approach. That cut development time significantly without changing the instructional logic.</p>

    <img src="{{ '/images/projects/guided-notes-example.png' | url }}" alt="Example of guided notes for Psychological Foundations module" class="post-featured-image" />

    <p>One thing I learned from teaching with these materials at Davidson College: early versions were too granular. Students would hunt for one missing word instead of engaging with the concept. I shifted toward more holistic outlines that invite synthesis rather than transcription. A small change that made a real difference in how students actually used them.</p>

    <p>When guided notes launched in Intro Psychology, faculty reported that students came to class better oriented and more ready to discuss. Lumen's sales team started using them as a differentiator with institutional partners. They eventually became standard practice and are now provided across all our courses.</p>

